## Recommended: Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is an established NuGet package purpose-built for exactly this scenario — no need to write custom wrappers.

**1. Install:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));
manager.Save("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
Assert.False(manager.FolderExists("/nonexistent"));
```

**Key points:**
- Wrap only the methods you actually call (`ReadAllText`, `WriteAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) — `System.IO.Abstractions` covers all of them under one interface.
- Register as `AddSingleton` — the default `FileSystem` implementation is stateless.
- No mocking framework required — `MockFileSystem` provides an in-memory filesystem out of the box.

Once you've added the dependency and updated your classes, you can use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` approach to mechanically replace all existing call sites in bulk. Want me to help with that migration?
